body.p:
GLAM institutions (Galleries, Libraries, Archives, and Museums) host rich resources made available in the form of digital collections. Bibliographic databases, in particular, represent collections of references on specific topics, which can be leveraged to apply digital humanities (DH) methods. Approaches such as "Collections as Data", "Labs" and the FAIR principles promote the publication of digital collections that support computational access (Padilla et al. 2019, Wilkinson et al. 2016). Jupyter Notebooks have emerged as a powerful tool to provide reproducible code (Candela et al.

2023
).
